body:
When creating ViewModels that update UI state in SwiftUI views, annotate the class with @MainActor to ensure all state mutations happen on the main thread.

Example:
```swift
@MainActor
@Observable
class MyViewModel {
  var items = [Item]()

  func loadData() async {
    items = await fetchItems()
  }
}
```

For Swift 6 and later, prefer the new @Observable macro over ObservableObject with @Published properties. It's more performant and works better with SwiftUI.

Old pattern (avoid):
```swift
class ViewModel: ObservableObject {
  @Published var data = [Item]()
}
```

New pattern (preferred):
```swift
@Observable
class ViewModel {
  var data = [Item]()
}
```

Prefer async/await and Task groups over completion handlers or Combine for concurrent operations.

Parallel loading:
```swift
async let repos = loadRepositories()
async let user = loadUser()
let (repositories, currentUser) = await (repos, user)
```

TaskGroup for dynamic concurrency:
```swift
await withTaskGroup(of: Item.self) { group in
  for id in ids {
    group.addTask { await fetchItem(id) }
  }
}
```

Use `as const` for literal objects and arrays that shouldn't be mutated. This gives better type inference and prevents accidental mutations.

```typescript
// Instead of:
const STATUS = { ACTIVE: 'active', INACTIVE: 'inactive' };
// type is { ACTIVE: string, INACTIVE: string }

// Use:
const STATUS = { ACTIVE: 'active', INACTIVE: 'inactive' } as const;
// type is { readonly ACTIVE: 'active', readonly INACTIVE: 'inactive' }
```

Test names should describe the behavior being tested, not just the method name.

❌ Bad:
```
func testLogin()
func testHandleError()
```

✅ Good:
```
func test_login_withValidCredentials_returnsUser()
func test_login_withInvalidPassword_throwsAuthError()
func test_handleError_whenNetworkUnavailable_showsRetryButton()
```

Define specific error types instead of using generic Error or strings. This enables better error handling and user feedback.

Swift:
```swift
enum NetworkError: LocalizedError {
  case connectionFailed
  case timeout
  case invalidResponse(Int)

  var errorDescription: String? {
    switch self {
    case .connectionFailed: return "Unable to connect"
    case .timeout: return "Request timed out"
    case .invalidResponse(let code): return "Server error (\(code))"
    }
  }
}
```
